<h2 id="text">Text</h2>
<h3>Transcripts</h3>
<p>
&ldquo;Text&rdquo; contains words transcribed from the manuscripts by the editors of <%= link_to 'editions', "#{about_path}#editions" %>. 
The text, if available, is determined by the edition or library context you choose; 
this can be changed using the menu provided (including your own transcripts, if you have signed in and created an edition). 
</p><p>
Some pages show only part of a larger work, while others contain many small works. 
Some pages have several alternative transcripts for each work, while others may only have one. 
And some pages include more text than has been transcribed by the available editions, while others include no text at all.
</p>
<h3>Line Breaks, Variant Words, and Notes</h3>
<p>
View information from editions about the text with the controls below. 
The  &ldquo;Line Breaks&rdquo; and &ldquo;Variant Words&rdquo; visualize (and hide) the selected edition&rsquo;s textual notes, if any.
Notes&rdquo; views this information as text instead, and may provide further clarification about the manuscript and transcript. 
Some editions do not include line breaks, variant words, or notes.
</p>
<h3>Metadata, Encoding, and Downloading</h3>
<p>
&ldquo;Metadata&rdquo; describes the source of the text in greater detail. 
&ldquo;Download as TEI&rdquo; saves the <%= link_to 'encoded text', "#{about_path}#encoding" %> and associated credits. 
<i>The text attribution must be included whenever the text is used under the terms of the Creative Commons license for this site</i>
(consult information about EDA <%= link_to 'Copyright & Terms of Use', terms_path %>).
</p>
<h3>Creating an Edition</h3>
<p>
To save your own edition, you will need to <%= link_to 'sign up/sign in', new_user_session_url %> to EDA. 
Your edition can be based on an existing edition&rsquo;s page order and transcripts or started from scratch.
Within your edition you may: include/hide pages, add/change metadata, change page order, and add your own transcripts.
Once saved, your edition is available for you to search for manuscript images and display as transcript text.
</p>

<h2 id="lexicon">Lexicon</h2>
<p>
Browse alphabetically through more than 9,000 words in Dickinson&rsquo;s poetry, as defined in her dictionary, Webster's 1844 <i>American Dictionary of the English Language</i>. 
Each word details a part of speech and definition&mdash;
often with many different senses. 
<%# From each lexicon entry, search for words in Dickinson&rsquo;s poems to see their use in context. %>
<%= link_to 'Resources', resources_path %> links to images of Dickinson&rsquo;s Webster&rsquo;s Dictionary under the Dickinson family library.
</p>

